MoneyBall (5 points, 1+2+1+1)¶

In the early 2000s, 2 baseball scouts completely changed the game of baseball by analysing the available data about baseball players and hiring the best ones. The MoneyBall dataset contains this data (click the link for more details). The goal is to accurately predict the number of 'runs' each player can score.

from pandas.tools.plotting import scatter_matrix

Many of the features in the dataset have discrete values, but all of them are already encoded as numeric values. Two of the features ("League" and "Playoffs") are binary and can only assume value 0 or 1. Among the features with continuous values, "OBP", "SLG" and "BA" seem to have a linear correlation to the target, as we can see from the scatter plots. We also plotted a separate scatter matrix, to emphasize the strict correlation between these three features and the target values.

In other features, such as "RA" and "W", the plot is a bit more sparse but it is still possible to visually identify some correlation. "OOBP" and "OSLG", on the other hand, have a very low correlation to the target, and therefore these two features will not be particularly useful in the prediction of target values. The visualized plots do not show many outliers in the dataset.

Four of the features have missing values: "RankSeason", "RankPlayoffs", "OOBP", "OSLG". We will drop these features in order to work on the dataset.

From the obtained cross-validation scores, we can observe that the Linear Regression model has the same result with and without scaling, while all the other models benefit significatively from scaling. The reason for this is that scaling is effective for all the models in which some kind of regularization is applied, while in the linear model it can be useful for interpreting the data, but it does not affect the actual regression model. In all regularized models scaling brings a significative improvement, but the model in which scaling has the strongest effect is the K-Neighbors Regressor: it changes the avarage R^2 score from 0.53 to 0.82.

Since the Linear Regression model does not allow for L1/L2 regularization, we tried to optimize it by adding polyomial features, to introduce non-linearity in the model. We tried several polynomial degrees and we found the optimal one to be 2.

In [27]:
# Linear regression with polynomial features
from sklearn.preprocessing import PolynomialFeatures
best_score = 0
lr_scores = []

for degree in [2,3,5,7]:
    poly = PolynomialFeatures(degree=degree, include_bias=False).fit(X_train_scaled)
    X_train_poly = poly.transform(X_train_scaled)
    X_test_poly = poly.transform(X_test_scaled)

    reg = LinearRegression().fit(X_train_poly, y_train)
    score = reg.score(X_test_poly, y_test)
    lr_scores.append(score)
    if score > best_score:
        best_score = score
        best_parameters = {'degree': degree}

print("Best score: {:.6f}".format(best_score))
print("Best parameters: {}".format(best_parameters))

Best score: 0.948745
Best parameters: {'degree': 2}

# Elastic Net (L1/L2 tradeoff)
best_score = 0
en_scores = pd.DataFrame(columns=range_01)

for alpha in range_01:
    row = []
    for l1_ratio in range_01:
        en = ElasticNet(alpha=alpha, l1_ratio=l1_ratio).fit(X_train_scaled, y_train)
        score = en.score(X_test_scaled, y_test)
        row.append(score)
        if score > best_score:
            best_score = score
            best_parameters = {'alpha': alpha, 'l1_ratio': l1_ratio}
    en_scores.loc[alpha] = row
        
# plot the mean cross-validation scores
scores = en_scores.values
mglearn.tools.heatmap(scores, xlabel='L1 ratio', xticklabels=range_01,
ylabel='Alpha', yticklabels=range_01, cmap="viridis");

print("Best score: {:.6f}".format(best_score))
print("Best parameters: {}".format(best_parameters))

Best score: 0.950886
Best parameters: {'alpha': 0.1, 'l1_ratio': 1}

Overview of the optimized performances:

Linear regression -> Best score: 0.948528 (for degree = 2)
Ridge -> Best score: 0.950848 (for alpha = 1)
Lasso -> Best score: 0.950886 (for alpha = 0.1)
Elastic Net -> Best score: 0.950886 (for alpha = 0.1, l1_ratio = 1)

We tried to improve the Linear Regression performance by adding flexibility, through additional polynomial features. The optimal score, which is significatively better than the default lineal model score, was found for a polynomial degree of 2.

When using Ridge Regression, which adopts L2 regularization, the best R^2 score is obtained for the maximal value of alpha (1), meaning that the model benefits from a very strong regularization to reduce the variance of estimates. Contrarily, in the Lasso model (based on L1 regulatization) the optimal value is found for a very low but not minimale value of alpha (0.1), implying that a stronger regularization is counterproductive.

In the Elastic Net model, the optimal value corresponds to a L1 ratio of 1 (full L1 penalty) and an alpha value of 0.1, which brings us back to the same properties and same R^2 score of the Lasso model. As visible from the heatmap, the worst performances are located in the top-left corner, which represents L2 regularization for a high alpha parameter, while all other corners of the map show fairly high R^2 values.

L2 prefers to have many small values, while L1 gives a better performance for many values close to 0 and some very large values, making it robust to ouliers. Interpreting our results, which finds in L1 regularization the best option for our model, we could probably achieve an even better result with a more detailed preprocessing of the data, focused on outliers removal.

The scores were normalized in order to easily indentify the most imporant features in each model. The optimized linear models have very similiar coefficients, as visible from the graph above, while the RandomForest has some similarities but also some notable differences. In both cases "Team", "League", "Year", "BA", "Playoffs" and "G", have relatively small importance, while "SLG" has maximal importance. But while in Random Forest "RA" and "W" have very low importance (and "OBP" relatively low), in the linear models their scores are significatively high.

Ultimately, the most important feature to consider when scouting for a baseball player are (in order): "SLG", "OBP", "W" and "RA", which is quite coherent to what we supposed in the data exploration section, but with some unexpected changes.

from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
import time;

l = [0.5, 1, 1.5, 2, 2.5, 3, 3.5, 4, 4.5, 5]

knn_scores = []
knn_time = []

for z in l:
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, stratify=y, test_size = ((z/10)*0.25), train_size = ((z/10)*0.75))
    
    # kNN 
    start_time = time.time()
    clf = KNeighborsClassifier(n_jobs=-1).fit(X_train, y_train) 
    knn_scores.append("%.2f" % float(format(clf.score(X_test, y_test))))
    end_time = time.time()
    
    knn_time.append((end_time-start_time))

#Random Forest
from sklearn.model_selection import ShuffleSplit
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier

rf_metrics = {}
for n in np.logspace(0, 10, num=11, base=2).astype(int):
    
    rf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=n, random_state=2)

    # Bootstraps
    n_repeat = 100
    shuffle_split = ShuffleSplit(test_size=0.33, n_splits=n_repeat)

    # Store sample predictions
    y_all_pred = [[] for _ in range(len(y))]

    # Train classifier on each bootstrap and score predictions
    for i, (train_index, test_index) in enumerate(shuffle_split.split(X)):
        # Train and predict
        rf.fit(X[train_index], y[train_index])
        y_pred = rf.predict(X[test_index])

        # Store predictions
        for i,index in enumerate(test_index):
            y_all_pred[index].append(y_pred[i])
        
    # Compute bias, variance, error
    bias_sq = sum([ (1 - x.count(y[i])/len(x))**2 * len(x)/n_repeat 
                for i,x in enumerate(y_all_pred) if len(x)>0])
    var = sum([((1 - ((x.count(0)/len(x))**2 + (x.count(1)/len(x))**2))/2) * len(x)/n_repeat
               for i,x in enumerate(y_all_pred) if len(x)>0])
    error = sum([ (1 - x.count(y[i])/len(x)) * len(x)/n_repeat 
                for i,x in enumerate(y_all_pred) if len(x)>0])
    
    rf_metrics[n] = {}
    rf_metrics[n]['bias'] = bias_sq
    rf_metrics[n]['var'] = var
    rf_metrics[n]['error'] = error
    
for n in rf_metrics:
    print("Metrics for %d trees -> Bias squared: %.2f, Variance: %.2f, Total error: %.2f" % (n, rf_metrics[n]['bias'], rf_metrics[n]['var'], rf_metrics[n]['error']))

The first difference that we can observe in the two graphs is that Random Forest has a notably higher variance, which then decreases with for higher numbers of trees, while Gradient Boosting has a variance that is almost null in the beginning and tends to increase. The general error in the beginning is much higher in the Gradient Boost model, but with the increasing of the number of trees it tends towards the same value (~800) for both models.

Let us first analyze the two cases separately. In Random Forest, when starting out with a single estimator, the bias and the variance values are equivalent. The bias grows slighly for two estimators, but then remains quite stable throughout the graph. Variance, on the other hand, steadily decreases when using a higher number of estimators, tending towards zero. This behavior is cause by an initial overfitting of the model, which is then gradually corrected.

In Gradient Boosting, contrarily, variance is quite steady, and it even increases slightly with higher numbers of estimators, while bias is improves throughout the graph. In fact, the plot shows a very high bias value for a single estimators, then the value decreases strongly for 4 estimators and it continues to decrease gradually. This is justified by an underfitting of the model.

Generally, both models benefit from a high number of estimateros: with around 128 estimators, they perform with very similiar error values. The reasons for this improvement is specular in the two models: in Random Forest the initial model is too complex, and it overfits the training data, while in Gradient Boosting the model is initially too simple and not enough flexible, underfitting the data. We should also note that while one of the two metrics is improoving the other gets worse, resulting in the risk to either underfit (in Random Forset) or overfit (in Gradient Boosting) the model, for excessively high numbers of estimators.

Discuss the effect of the different combinations learning rate and tree depth and provide a clear explanation.

  • While scikit-learn has a validation_curve function, we'll use a modified version (below) that provides a lot more detail and can be used to study more than one hyperparameter. You can use a default train-test split.
In [34]:
# Plots validation curves for every classifier in clfs. 
# Also indicates the optimal result by a vertical line
# Uses 1-AUROC, so lower is better
from sklearn.metrics import roc_auc_score

def validation_curve(clfs, X_test, y_test, X_train, y_train):
    plt.figure(figsize=(13,6))
    for n,clf in enumerate(clfs):
        test_score = np.empty(len(clf.estimators_))
        train_score = np.empty(len(clf.estimators_))

        for i, pred in enumerate(clf.staged_decision_function(X_test)):
            test_score[i] = 1-roc_auc_score(y_test, pred)

        for i, pred in enumerate(clf.staged_decision_function(X_train)):
            train_score[i] = 1-roc_auc_score(y_train, pred)

        best_iter = np.argmin(test_score)
        learn = clf.get_params()['learning_rate']
        depth = clf.get_params()['max_depth']
        test_line = plt.plot(test_score, '-',
                             label='learn=%.1f depth=%i (%.2f)'%(learn,depth,
                                                                 test_score[best_iter]))

        colour = test_line[-1].get_color()
        plt.plot(train_score, '--', color=colour)
        
        plt.xlabel("Number of boosting iterations")
        plt.ylabel("1 - area under ROC")
        plt.axvline(x=best_iter, color=colour)
        
    plt.legend(loc='best')

As we can see in the first graph, the classifiers with maximum tree depth of 1 have in most cases higher AUROC values than the ones with 4, but with some exceptions. To analyze this behavior let us observe the third plot: here the learning rate is the same for all curves and depth changes from 1, to 3, to 7. If you only consder the test score (dashed lines) we can see the the higher the depth is, the better the perfomance. In reality, for a high number of boosting iteration the model tends to overfit: we can see that already for 20 boosting iterations depth=3 has better test performances than depth=7, and they remain very similiar throughout the graph. We can conclude that, in these particular case, reasing the maximum depth to 3 improves the classification, but after that it becomes counterproductive. We can also observe this in the first plot, in which the two models with max depth=4 show a great difference between test score and train score, caused by overfitting.

In the second plot we can observe the behavior of three model in which the max depth is stable at 3, while the learning rate varies from 0.1, to 0.5 to 1. We can see that while for low numbers of iteration a high rate results in better performance: starting from 50 iterations, the higher the learning rate and the more the model overfits. This is also emphasized by the great difference between test curves and train curves: the case of learning rate=1, for example, very rapidly starts to overfit and for a number of iterations of 70 or more it has the worst test performance out of the three cases.
